The cantilever 3D printer is a fascinating niche within the domain of additive manufacturing that involves the use of a solitary vertical Z-axis pillar that holds up a horizontal X-axis bar from just one side. In contrast to double post gantry 3D printers, cantilever 3D printers make use of the inverted T or C-type motion pattern wherein the print head is moved by the unsupported bar as the heated bed traverses in the perpendicular direction along the Y axis. Thanks to its simple mechanism, cantilever systems remain extremely affordable, portable, and light-weight in nature; hence, such printers are perfect for usage in classrooms or small workshops. Although the cantilever structure makes it easy to access the print bed, there are certain engineering disadvantages in relation to the principles of physics and size. Given that the horizontal arm works like a lever, fast motions made by the print head may cause vibrations and even slight sagging of the unsupported arm, resulting in ringing on the prints. As a result, cantilever printers are limited by their build volume and use light print heads to prevent bowing.
